  "enhanced_information": "Aspirin is contraindicated in peptic ulcer due to its mechanism of inhibiting prostaglandins, which leads to an increase in stomach acid secretion and can aggravate peptic ulcers. This is supported by the evidence path linking aspirin with prostaglandins and their role in gastric physiology. In contrast, aspirin is not contraindicated in fever, unstable angina, or myalgia. It has anti-inflammatory properties that reduce fever and alleviate pain from myalgia, and its antiplatelet effect is beneficial in preventing blood clot formation, which is crucial in the management of unstable angina."
